Inside the `complete()` method, `this` is the current object, i.e. the object passed as argument to `subscribe()`. Not the component. 

Use arrow functions. 

See [stackblitz.com/edit/angular-zkry2p][1] for a demo:

    // not working
    of(&#39;hello 1&#39;).subscribe({
      next(prefix) {
        console.log(prefix + &#39; &#39; + this.name);
      }
    });

    // working
    of(&#39;hello 2&#39;).subscribe(prefix =&gt; console.log(prefix + &#39; &#39; + this.name)
    );

    // also working
    of(&#39;hello 3&#39;).subscribe({
      next: prefix =&gt; console.log(prefix + &#39; &#39; + this.name)
    });


  [1]: https://stackblitz.com/edit/angular-zkry2p

`complete` method uses a function syntax which has a different `this`. Instead of passing functions, you can use arrow function which will retain `this` property of the parent.

    initialData() {
        this.workspacesService.getWorkspaces().subscribe(
          ws =&gt; { //&lt;--- arrow function
            
              this.workspaces = ws;
              console.log(this.workspaces);
            },
         err =&gt; {
            },
         () =&gt; { //&lt;--- arrow function
              this.workspaces.forEach((ws) =&gt; {
                if (ws.workspace_id == null) {
                  console.log(this.wsnodes);
                  this.wsnodes.push(new WorkspaceFlatNode(ws.id, ws.name, true, 0, true))
                }
              });
              console.log(&quot;completed&quot;);
              console.log(this.wsnodes);
            }
        );
      }


Assuming that you&#39;re calling `getChildren` method before the `this.workspacesService.getWorkspaces()` has completed, `this.workspaces` does not have any data. 
Once the `this.workspacesService.getWorkspaces()` completes, only then the `workspaces` array will be populated.

